Freally Teleprompt — third-party data notices
=============================================

This file covers third-party DATA bundled in Freally Teleprompt. Source-code
dependencies are covered separately by THIRD-PARTY.md (fonts) and the Rust/npm
dependency manifests.

This notice ships inside the installer, not only in the repository. The licence
below is an attribution licence: crediting the source is not a courtesy, it is
the condition under which the data may be redistributed at all — and every copy
of the app is a redistribution.


Autocomplete word and phrase tables (FT-20 / FT-21 / FT-22)
-----------------------------------------------------------

The script editor's ghost-text autocomplete completes against tables bundled in
the installer, one per app language, at `ui/src/dict/<locale>.json`. They are a
plain prefix lookup: no model, no inference, no network. Nothing about them is
ever downloaded at runtime, and nothing the operator types is ever transmitted.

SOURCE — the Tatoeba Project, https://tatoeba.org
LICENCE — Creative Commons Attribution 2.0 France (CC BY 2.0 FR)
          https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/fr/deed.en

    Contains data from the Tatoeba Project (https://tatoeba.org), licensed
    under CC BY 2.0 FR.

All eighteen tables — Arabic, Chinese (Simplified), Dutch, English, French,
German, Hindi, Indonesian, Italian, Japanese, Korean, Polish, Portuguese
(Brazil), Russian, Spanish, Turkish, Ukrainian and Vietnamese — are derived from
that one corpus and no other. The word and phrase lists are frequency counts
computed over its sentences by `scripts/build-dicts.mjs`, which is committed
alongside the tables so the derivation can be re-run and re-audited.

CC BY 2.0 FR permits commercial use and redistribution, and imposes no
share-alike or non-commercial term. It is deliberately the ONLY data licence
here: each additional source would be another obligation to honour in every
release and to re-verify whenever the tables are rebuilt.


Sources deliberately NOT used
-----------------------------

Recorded because their absence is a decision, not an oversight, and because the
next person to extend these tables will be tempted by exactly these:

  * Leipzig Corpora Collection / Wortschatz Leipzig — the corpus downloads are
    offered for "non-commercial personal and scientific purposes" under CC BY-NC.
    A non-commercial licence cannot ship inside a paid installer. (Their separate
    *Frequency Dictionaries* CD-ROM word lists are CC BY 3.0 and would be usable;
    the free corpus downloads that people generally reach for are not.)

  * Wikipedia, Wiktionary and derived frequency lists — CC BY-SA. The share-alike
    term reaches the work they are distributed in.

  * SCOWL / the English Speller Database — permissive and commercially usable,
    but at size 80 and above it incorporates the UK Advanced Cryptics Dictionary,
    whose licence requires its notice be "prominently displayed and the text of
    this document ... included verbatim". Usable with care; not needed, because
    Tatoeba already covers English.

  * OpenSubtitles-derived frequency lists — the wrapper repositories are often
    MIT-licensed while the underlying subtitle text is not theirs to relicense.

If you add a source, add it to this file in the same commit, and read its licence
at the source rather than trusting a summary of it — including this one.
